<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How long does it really take to get over a breakup?", answer: "A 2007 study from the University of Arkansas found the average breakup recovery is about 11 weeks for short-to-medium relationships and roughly half the length of the relationship for longer ones — so a 2-year relationship typically takes 12 months, a 5-year relationship takes 2.5 years. These are averages with huge variation. Some people bounce back in weeks; some take years. Whether you initiated the breakup, whether it was your first love, and whether it was a marriage all change the timeline." },
  { question: "Why does my breakup hurt so much?", answer: "Breakup pain isn't just emotional — fMRI studies from Columbia University show that romantic rejection activates the same brain regions as physical pain. Your brain treats losing a partner like losing a limb, especially in the first weeks. This is also why people describe heartbreak as a physical sensation — chest pain, exhaustion, loss of appetite. The good news is that this acute phase fades within weeks; the longer-term grieving takes months but feels much less overwhelming." },
  { question: "Should I stay friends with my ex?", answer: "Most therapists say no — at least not in the first 6–12 months. Staying in contact reactivates the attachment system and prevents the brain from moving on. The 'no contact rule' (no texts, no social media, no in-person meetings) is the single most-recommended intervention from breakup recovery research. After about a year, friendship can sometimes work, especially if both people have moved on. Before that, contact almost always slows recovery." },
  { question: "What helps with breakup recovery?", answer: "The most evidence-backed interventions: regular exercise (releases endorphins, restores sleep, builds confidence), social connection (friends and family, not new dating), therapy or counseling (especially CBT for negative thought patterns), journaling (helps process emotions and gain perspective), and creating new routines (the brain associates places and habits with the ex, so changing routines breaks those associations). Avoid: rebound relationships, social media stalking, alcohol, and trying to win them back." },
  { question: "When should I start dating again?", answer: "There's no universal rule, but most therapists recommend waiting until you can think about the ex without strong emotion (love or hate), and until you can meet someone new without comparing them to the ex. For most people that's 3–12 months, depending on the relationship length and intensity. Rebound relationships (dating immediately after a breakup to numb the pain) usually delay healing rather than speed it up, even when they feel good in the moment." }
]) %>

